The Borana people of Ethiopia and Kenya are in no rush to name their newborn babies. They may wait for up to three years before finally naming their babies. “Until you name them, you just call them by random names of your choice.” The main reason for this is that naming ceremonies only happen occasionally and often they have to wait for some time. <span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span> [Source: BBC] Vanguard News Nigeria. When last week the President of the United States of America created a new “Nambia” country in the African continent, we all laughed and questioned his intelligence September 24, 2017 In "Diaspora Matters" Whatever we may be going through, worry is never the solution to any problem. If anything, it compounds problems. The solution lies in our relationship with the Lord July 23, 2017 In "Joyful Homes" A baby thought to be just a few hours old when it was found was abandoned at a roadside, in Igbogbo, Ikorodu area Lagos state. The newborn baby boy, who weighed 2.7 pounds, was discovered by a woman going about her daily business activities at the early hours of Tuesday… December 10, 2011 In "Just Human"